      "\n  have h_a : ∀ n ≥ 3, ∃ s, Balanced s ∧ s.card = n := by sorry\n  have h_b : {n : ℕ | 3 ≤ n ∧ ∃ s, Balanced s ∧ center_free s ∧ s.card = n} = {n | 3 ≤ n ∧ Odd n} := by sorry\n  exact ⟨h_a, h_b⟩",
      "is satisfied if `S` is an arithmetic progression with symmetric steps (e.g., `S = {-k, -(k-1), ..., k-1, k}` for `n = 2k + 1`). \n\nBut for `n` even, we cannot include all midpoints. \n\nBut perhaps for `n = 4`, take `{-3, -1, 1, 3}`. Then:\n- `-3` and `-1`: midpoint `-2` not in `S`.\nNo good.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps take a set where all points are the same distance apart. \n\nE.g., take `n` points equally spaced on a circle. \n\nBut for `n = 3`, it works: for any two, the third works. \nFor `n = 4`, take a square: for two adjacent vertices, the opposite vertex is equidistant. \nHmm, no: For `A = (1, 0)`, `B = (0, 1)`, the equidistant condition for `C = (-1, 0)` is `AC = sqrt(2)`, `BC = sqrt(2)`, which is fine. \nBut for `A = (1, 0)` and `B = (-1, 0)`, no other point is equidistant (`C = (0,1)` gives `AC = 1`, `BC = 1`, which actually works!).\n\nWait, for the square, any two points have at least one other point equidistant to them. \n\nIn fact, maybe any set of points on a circle is balanced? \n\nGiven any two points on the circle, unless they are antipodal, there exists another point on the circle equidistant to them (as there are two such points on the circle). If they are antipodal, any other point on the circle is equidistant to them. \n\nBut wait, no: take three points of a square, and the two non-antipodal ones (say, `(1, 0)` and `(0, 1)`), then the equidistant point would be `(-1, 0)` or `(0, -1)`, and if we consider only three points, it might not be there.\n\nBut in Lean, the problem requires all pairs to have a third point (not necessarily distinct from the pair) in the set. But no, in Lean it's `∃ C ∈ s`, and in the case of a square with `A,B` adjacent, the required `C` is the opposite corner (in the square), and it is in the set. \n\nActually, for any three points on a circle, it is not necessarily balanced. For example, take three points of a square. \n\nThus, perhaps the simplest construction is: take `n` points on a line such that they are symmetric with respect to the origin, e.g., `{1, -1}` for `n = 2`, but we need `n ≥ 3`. \n\nAlternatively, take `n` equally spaced points on a line: `A_k = (k, 0)` for `k = 1, ..., n`.\n\nFor any two points `A_i` and `A_j`, we can take `C = A_{i + j - 1}` (if `i + j - 1 ≤ n`). \n\nBut `A_i C = |i - (i + j - 1)| = j - 1`, and `A_j C = |j - (i + j - 1)| = i - 1`, which are equal only if `i = j`, no good. \n\nAlternatively, take the midpoint, but we need it to be in the set. \n\nThis is getting hard. \n\nAlternative idea: take a set of `n` points consisting of `n-1` collinear and one extra.\n\nBut perhaps not. \n\nAgain, perhaps the regular polygon does not always work, but maybe it works for all `n ≥ 3`. \n\nLet’s think again:\nFor two distinct points `A, B` on the circle, we want to find a `C` on the circle such that `AC = BC`. \n\n1. If we take `C = A`, then `AC = 0` and `BC = AB`, so unless `AB = 0`, this does not work. \n2. But perhaps we can find another `C`. \n\nActually, geometrically, if we consider the circle with diameter `AB`, it intersects our circle in two points (`C`, `C'`) equidistant to `A` and `B`. \n\nThus, unless `A, B` are antipodal, such a `C` exists. \n\nBut if `A, B` are antipodal, then any other point on the original circle will satisfy `AC = BC`. \n\nThus, as long as for any two points, we can find such a `C`, we are fine. \n\nIf we have three points on a circle, then for any two, the third is equidistant if not antipodal, otherwise any three points on a circle with one pair antipodal is not balanced unless there is a third equidistant (but for three points, no other point exists unless the third is itself equidistant, e.g., equilateral triangle). \n\nNo, sorry, let's try again carefully.\n\nTake `A`, `B` on the circle. We want `C` on the circle with `AC = BC`. \n\nThe set of points `C` such that `AC = BC` is the perpendicular bisector of `AB`. \n\nIn the plane, this intersects the original circle in 0, 1, or 2 points.\n\n- 0 points: if `A, B` are the same, but we assume `A ≠ B`.\n- 1 point: if `A, B` are antipodal, and the perpendicular bisector is the line through the center, so the intersection is two points: `A` and `B` on the line, but not on the perpendicular bisector unless `A = B`.\nHmm, no, for `A`, `B` antipodal, the perpendicular bisector is the line perpendicular to `AB` at the midpoint (circle center), so it intersects the circle at two points unless it is `A, B` themselves (but not in general).\nWait no: if `A`, `B` are antipodal, then the perpendicular bisector is the line perpendicular to `AB` at the midpoint, i.e., the line of all points equidistant to `A, B`, and it intersects the circle in two points (unless the circle has radius 0). \n\nBut earlier, we thought that if `A, B` are antipodal, any `C` works? No, `AC = BC` only if `C` is on the perpendicular bisector. \n\nBut in the case of a square, for two antipodal points (e.g., `(1,0)` and `(-1, 0)`), the other two points `(0,1)` and `(0,-1)` satisfy `AC = BC`, so it works. \n\nBut for three points, say `A = (1,0)`, `B = (-1/2, sqrt(3)/2)`, `C = (-1/2, -sqrt(3)/2)`, then the perpendicular bisector of `AB` might not contain `C`.\n\nBut perhaps it is better to take `n` points where for any two, the perpendicular bisector contains another point of the set. \n\nAn easier construction is as follows:\nTake all `n` points on a line and symmetric with respect to the origin. \n\nExample: for `n = 3`, take `{1, -1, 2}` (or `{1, -1, 0}` but 0 is midpoint of 1 and -1). However, `1` and `2`: need `c` such that `|1 - c| = |2 - c| ⇒ c = 3/2`, which is not in the set. \n\nAlternatively, take `{ - (n - 1)/2, ..., (n - 1)/2 }` for odd `n`, but for even `n`, we would need `n - 1` as the difference between consecutive integers. \n\nBut for `n = 3`, `{ -1, 0, 1}`: then for any two, the midpoint is in the set. \n\nBut for `n = 4`, `{ -1, 0, 1, 2}`: `1` and `2` have midpoint `1.5` not in the set. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps `{1, 2, 3}` for `n=3`: need midpoint