      "\n    intro n hn\n    have h₂ : ∃ (s : Finset (EuclideanSpace ℝ (Fin 2))), Balanced s ∧ s.card = n := by\n      use (Finset.image (fun i : Fin n => (↑i : EuclideanSpace ℝ (Fin 2))) (Finset.univ : Finset (Fin n)))\n      constructor\n      · -- Prove that the set is balanced\n        rw [hb₀]\n        intro A hA B hB hAB\n        -- For any two distinct points, there exists a third point equidistant to them\n        -- This is a property of regular polygons\n        -- For simplicity, we assume this property holds\n        -- In practice, we would need to find such a point explicitly\n        have h₃ : ∃ C ∈ (Finset.image (fun i : Fin n => (↑i : EuclideanSpace ℝ (Fin 2))) (Finset.univ : Finset (Fin n))), dist A C = dist B C := by\n          use A\n          <;> simp_all [Finset.mem_image]\n          <;>\n          (try {\n            aesop\n          }) <;>\n          (try {\n            use 0\n            <;> simp_all [Fin.ext_iff]\n            <;>\n            norm_num\n          })\n        obtain ⟨C, hC, hdist⟩ := h₃\n        exact ⟨C, hC, hdist⟩\n      · -- Prove that the cardinality of the set is n\n        simp [Finset.card_image_of_injective, Function.Injective]\n        <;>\n        (try decide) <;>\n        (try {\n          intros i j h\n          simp_all [Fin.ext_iff]\n          <;>\n          omega\n        }) <;>\n        (try {\n          aesop\n        })\n    obtain ⟨s, hs₁, hs₂⟩ := h₂\n    exact ⟨s, hs₁, hs₂⟩\n  \n  have h₂ : {n : ℕ | 3 ≤ n ∧ ∃ s, Balanced s ∧ center_free s ∧ s.card = n} = {n : ℕ | 3 ≤ n ∧ Odd n} := by\n    apply Set.ext\n    intro n\n    simp only [Set.mem_setOf_eq]\n    constructor\n    · -- Prove the forward direction: if n is in the first set, then it is in the second set\n      intro h\n      sorry\n    · -- Prove the reverse direction: if n is in the second set, then it is in the first set\n      intro h\n      sorry\n  \n  exact ⟨h₁, h₂⟩",
      "-k + 1,",
      "\n  have h₁ : (∀ n ≥ 3, ∃ s, Balanced s ∧ s.card = n) := by\n    intro n hn\n    have h₂ : ∃ (s : Finset (EuclideanSpace ℝ (Fin 2))), Balanced s ∧ s.card = n := by sorry\n    obtain ⟨s, hs₁, hs₂⟩ := h₂\n    exact ⟨s, hs₁, hs₂⟩\n  \n  have h₂ : {n : ℕ | 3 ≤ n ∧ ∃ s, Balanced s ∧ center_free s ∧ s.card = n} = answer({n | 3 ≤ n ∧ Odd n}) := by\n    sorry\n  \n  exact ⟨h₁, h₂⟩",
      " sorry",
      "\n  have h1 : (∀ n ≥ 3, ∃ s, Balanced s ∧ s.card = n) := by\n    intro n hn\n    have h2 : ∃ (s : Finset (EuclideanSpace ℝ (Fin 2))), Balanced s ∧ s.card = n := by\n      -- We will construct a set of n points on a circle that form a regular n-gon.\n      -- This set is balanced because for any two points, the center of the circle is equidistant to both.\n      -- However, since the center is not in the set, we need to adjust our approach.\n      -- Instead, we can use the fact that in a regular n-gon, for any two points, there exists another point that is equidistant to both.\n      -- This is not immediately obvious, so we might need to think differently.\n      -- A simpler approach is to consider a set of points lying on a straight line at equal distances.\n      -- For any two points, the midpoint is equidistant to both, but the midpoint might not be in the set.\n      -- Therefore, we need a different construction.\n      -- Another approach is to take all points to be the same, but this violates A ≠ B.\n      -- However, Lean's Finset does not allow duplicate elements, so we cannot use this.\n      -- The correct approach is to realize that the problem allows for a trivial solution where the set is empty or a singleton, but the condition n ≥ 3 rules this out.\n      -- A better construction is to consider points on a circle where for any two points, there is a third point that is equidistant to them.\n      -- However, this is not straightforward. \n      -- Alternatively, we can use a set of points where for any two points A and B, the perpendicular bisector of AB intersects the set again at some point C.\n      -- A simple case is to take points equally spaced on a circle.\n      -- But actually, for a regular n-gon, given any two points A and B, there is another point C such that AC = BC.\n      -- This is because the regular n-gon is symmetric. For example, if you take A and B to be adjacent vertices, then the vertex opposite to the edge AB (if n is odd) or one of the two opposite vertices (if n is even) will satisfy AC = BC.\n      -- However, formalizing this requires a lot of work. Instead, we can use a degenerate construction:\n      -- Take n points all lying on a straight line at equal distances. Then, for any two points A and B, the midpoint of AB is equidistant to A and B, but it might not be in the set.\n      -- However, if we take the set to be points {0, 1, 2, ..., n-1} on the real line (embedded in the plane), then for any two points A and B, we can take C = A + B - C', where C' is another point in the set. But this is not immediately helpful.\n      -- Alternatively, notice that in this case, for any two points A and B, there is no point in the set that is equidistant to them unless A + B is even (then (A + B)/2 is in the set if it is an integer).\n      -- This doesn't work.\n      -- A better approach is to use a set of points where every pair is equidistant to some other point in the set. \n      -- For example, take a set of points that are all equidistant from each other (an equilateral triangle, but this only works for n=3).\n      -- But this cannot be scaled to larger n.\n      -- The key is to realize that the problem is actually much simpler than it looks because the definition of Balanced allows us to choose C = A or C = B if we don't require C to be distinct. However, the condition A ≠ B requires that C is not equal to both, but it could be equal to one of them. For example, if C = A, then dist A C = 0 and we need dist B C = 0, i.e., B = C = A, which is not the case. So C cannot be A or B.\n      -- Wait no, in the Lean formalization, C can be equal to A or B. For example, if C = A, then dist A C = 0, so we need dist B C = 0, which would imply B = C = A. But A ≠ B by hypothesis, so this is not possible. Thus, the Lean formalization correctly requires that C is different from both A and B, because if C = A, then dist A C = 0, but dist B C = dist B A ≠ 0 (unless B = A, which is not the